data.title: MURRAY TO BRING HIS STICKS, SCHTICK TO OUTBACK EVENT
data.meta_description: Golf's most famous fictional greenskeeper is coming to the Outback Steakhouse Pro-Am in two weeks. Actor and comedian Bill Murray, who played Carl Spackler in Caddyshack, will compete in the...
data.text:
Golf's most famous fictional greenskeeper is coming to the Outback Steakhouse Pro-Am in two weeks. Actor and comedian Bill Murray, who played Carl Spackler in Caddyshack, will compete in the Champions Tour event at the TPC of Tampa Bay, Feb. 16-18. Murray, an avid golfer who has been prominent on the pro-am circuit, is expected to play with Tour player Scott Simpson, his longtime partner at the Pebble Beach Pro-Am, where the two will compete next week.

The Outback tournament puts pros with amateurs for the first two rounds, with the top 16 teams advancing to the final round, when all of the pros compete for the title. Other celebrities who have committed are Huey Lewis, Joe Theismann, Derrick Brooks, Ronde Barber, Jim Courier and Ray Knight. For more information, see Ticket Window on page 2C.

HORSE RACING

Barbaro may lie in rest at Derby site

Barbaro's final resting place could be just a few hundred yards from the scene of his greatest triumph in the Kentucky Derby. Officials at the Kentucky Derby Museum, located on the grounds of Churchill Downs, said they would be "honored'' if Barbaro was buried in a garden on the grounds. "We feel like we're bringing horses back to be honored," said Lynn Ashton, executive director of the museum. The gravesites of Derby winners Sunny's Halo (1983), Carry Back (1961), Swaps (1955) and Brokers Tip (1933) are located at the museum. Owners Gretchen and Roy Jackson said a decision on Barbaro's burial site had not been made.

HIGH SCHOOLS

Marve to Miami?

Plant quarterback Robert Marve is expected to commit to the University of Miami during a news conference at 4 p.m. today at the football field house. "I'm looking for a team that really believes in me," Marve told the South Florida Sun-Sentinel. "I think I've found that." Marve, who led Plant to a state title, backed off an oral commitment to Alabama after Mike Shula was fired in November. Marve was noncommital when reached Tuesday evening.
